[1] South Africa (KwaZulu-Natal) equine, human exposure
Date: Tue 27 Feb 2018
Source: North Coast Courier [edited]
https://northcoastcourier.co.za/103904/rabid-horse-bites-doringkop-woman/


A local woman was on the receiving end of a rabies scare last week [week of 19 Feb 2018] when she was bitten by a horse. LM, who lives on a farm near Doringkop, inland from Stanger [KwaZulu-Natal], told the Courier she approached the horse on [Mon 19 Feb 2018] thinking it was sick. "It was lying down, which made me think maybe it had colic and then the best thing to do is try get them back up on their feet," she said.

While trying to help the horse, she got too close and was bitten. "Afterwards I was chatting with a family friend, a vet, about colic and she phoned back to say I should just check for rabies, though it was unlikely." However, the horse did in fact test positive for rabies and had to be euthanized that same day. LM as well as all her workers who had contact with the horse have since undergone prophylactic treatments so as to prevent the rabies virus from infecting them.

Rabies is a dread disease in humans and warm-blooded vertebrates, which is transmitted by the bite of an infected animal, most commonly dogs. The virus is present in the saliva of an infected person or animal.

In September last year [2017], a 2 year old died after contracting rabies from a dog bite. NM was bitten while playing near the community standpipe near his home in the Thafeni area of Upper Tongaat [KwaZulu-Natal]. According to his sister, F, their mother was out asking for food when the incident occurred. "After he was bitten by the dog, neighbours cleaned his wound with spirits and killed the dog," said F. She said no one thought he had been infected as he showed no signs of pain or illness and just continued playing [see comment]. Within 14 days he started showing symptoms and one day after that he passed away.

Director of veterinary services from the Department of Agriculture, Dr Themba Skhakhane has warned residents that every dog bite should be treated as a matter of urgency and the patient must get to the nearest clinic as soon as possible. "If you have ever seen someone infected with rabies, you would agree that it is a horrible way to die."

Quintin Doidge from the state vet clinic in Stanger urged residents not to touch any stray dogs but contact the SPCA or the state vet clinic, especially if they appear to be rabid. The state vet can be reached at 032 437 7500/4/9.

[byline: Allan Troskie]

--
communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

["No one thought he had been infected as he showed no signs of pain or illness" (following the dog bite) is a fatal (and, unfortunately, still prevailing) mistake. Clinical signs which may lead to suspicion of rabies will appear only after an incubation period which may take days (generally, at least a week), weeks, or even months. During this period the victim appears normal.

WHO's "first aid treatment":
"Since elimination of rabies virus at the site of infection by chemical or physical means is the most effective mechanism of protection, immediate washing and flushing with soap and water, detergent, or water alone are imperative (this procedure is recommended for all bite wounds, including those unrelated to possible exposure to rabies). Then apply either ethanol (700 ml/l) or tincture or aqueous solution of iodine.

"Treatment by, or under direction of a physician:
treat as described above and then:
- apply anti-rabies immunoglobulin by careful instillation in the depth of the wound and by infiltration around the wound;
- postpone suturing of the wound;
- if suturing is necessary, ensure that immunoglobulin has been applied locally as described above;
- where indicated, begin anti-tetanus treatment and administer antimicrobials and drugs to control infections other than rabies."
(http://www.who.int/rabies/human/firstaid/en/)

Local treatment of wounds involving possible exposure to rabies is recommended in all exposures. Treatment should be started as early as possible after exposure, but in no case should it be denied to exposed persons whatever time interval has elapsed. - Mod.AS

