[Rabies is on the rise in Thailand. There were 330 reported cases of rabies-affected animals in 2015, 614 in 2016, and 843 in 2017. Dogs were the most infected (89 per cent), followed by cattle (6.6 per cent), cats (3.6 per cent), and others (0.7 per cent). Rabies caused 5 human deaths in 2015, 14 in 2016, and 8 in 2017. Last month [January 2018] a schoolteacher in Mueang Surin (Surin province) who had 5 dogs at home and often fed stray dogs died as a result of a rabies infection. The above information was published by The Nation on 13 Feb 2018; see at http://www.nationmultimedia.com/detail/national/30338722. - Mod.TTM

Rabies is an OIE reportable disease; for further information addressing its prevention and control in animals, subscribers are encouraged to visit OIE's rabies portal at http://www.oie.int/en/animal-health-in-the-world/rabies-portal/prevention-and-control/. - Mod.AS

